IAM - Identity and Access Management
AWS IAM is a service that helps securly control access to AWS resources

IAM Components - Users, Groups, Roles, Policies, Access advisor, Credential report, Access Analyzer, Organization

Types of users : 1) Root User - The root user is created when the account is created    2) IAM User - IAM users are created by root user or an IAM administrator for the account

Managed policies :
1)AWS managed policies - created and managed by AWS
2)Customer managed policies - created and managed by AWS account owner

IAM user - An AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) user is an entity that you create in AWS to represent the person that uses it to interact with AWS.

MFA - Multi Factor Authentication is a best practice for extra layer security of protection on top username and password

Credentials report - You can generate and download the credentials report that list all users in your account and the status of their various credentials including passwords, 
access keys and MFA devices.
we can use credential report for auditing and compliance efforts 

User Groups - IAM user group is a collection of IAM users
              User group is a way to attach policies to multiple users at one time
              
              
Access Analyzer - AWS IAM access analyzer helps to identifies the resources in organization or account from access the zone of trust or not such as s3 buckets              
          
Policies - You manage access in AWS by creating policies and attaching them to IAM identities ( Users, group of users or roles, AWS resources )
           A policy is an object in AWS when it associated with resources, defines their permissions
           Permissions in policies defines whether the request is allowed or not
           Most of the policies are stored in AWS as a JSON documents 
           
